 {"id":"bd-10qj","title":"Barrier cancellation race: notification lost on checkpoint","description":"# Bug: Barrier Cancellation Race - Lost Notification

## Location
`src/sync/barrier.rs:92-108`

## Problem Description

When a waiter cancels at the barrier, there's a race condition where a notification 
can be lost if it arrives right as the cancellation checkpoint fails.

```rust
if cx.checkpoint().is_err() {
    if state.generation != local_gen {
        // Re-check generation in case we were woken
        return Ok(BarrierWaitResult { is_leader: false });
    }
    if state.arrived > 0 {
        state.arrived -= 1;
    }
    return Err(BarrierWaitError::Cancelled);
}
```

## Root Cause Analysis

The pattern checks generation after checkpoint failure, but:
1. Task is about to cancel (checkpoint returns error)
2. Another thread trips barrier AND wakes this task
3. Task proceeds with cancellation path
4. Generation check happens but doesn't prevent the error return

The task was legitimately woken to proceed, but the checkpoint error takes precedence.

## Race Window Timeline

```
T1 (cancelling):              T2 (tripping barrier):
─────────────────────         ─────────────────────
checkpoint() starts
                              increment arrived
                              generation++
                              wake T1
checkpoint() returns Err
check generation (changed!)
return Ok(...) <-- correct!
```

But if T1's checkpoint error is detected BEFORE T2's wake signal propagates:

```
T1 (cancelling):              T2 (tripping barrier):
─────────────────────         ─────────────────────
checkpoint() returns Err
check generation (same)
arrived -= 1
return Err(Cancelled) <-- WRONG!
                              increment arrived
                              generation++
                              wake T1 (too late)
```

## Impact

- Tasks that should have proceeded through barrier return Cancelled
- Can cause deadlock if barrier expects N tasks but some cancel incorrectly
- Subtle and hard to reproduce in testing

## Proposed Fix

Use a per-waiter notification flag instead of relying solely on generation:

```rust
struct BarrierWaiter {
    waker: Waker,
    notified: Arc<AtomicBool>,  // Set when barrier trips
}

// On barrier trip:
for waiter in waiters.drain(..) {
    waiter.notified.store(true, Ordering::Release);
    waiter.waker.wake();
}

// On cancel check:
if cx.checkpoint().is_err() {
    if self.notified.load(Ordering::Acquire) || state.generation != local_gen {
        return Ok(BarrierWaitResult { is_leader: false });
    }
    // Safe to cancel
}
```

## Comprehensive Testing Requirements

### Unit Tests
- [ ] `test_barrier_cancel_before_trip` - Cancel before barrier trips, verify clean cancel
- [ ] `test_barrier_cancel_after_trip` - Cancel after barrier trips, verify proceeds
- [ ] `test_barrier_cancel_during_trip` - Cancel exactly as barrier trips (race)
- [ ] `test_barrier_cancel_notified_flag` - Verify notified flag set on trip
- [ ] `test_barrier_cancel_generation_check` - Verify generation fallback works
- [ ] `test_barrier_cancel_arrived_decrement` - Verify count accurate after cancel
- [ ] `test_barrier_cancel_multiple` - Multiple tasks cancel simultaneously

### Stress Tests
```rust
#[test]
#[ignore]
fn stress_test_barrier_cancel_race() {
    // 10 tasks, 1000 barrier cycles
    // Each cycle: random subset cancels, rest proceeds
    // Verify: no task incorrectly cancels when it should proceed
    // Verify: no deadlock (barrier always eventually trips or all cancel)
    for seed in 0..100 {
        let barrier = Arc::new(Barrier::new(10));
        let results = Arc::new(Mutex::new(Vec::new()));

        for i in 0..10 {
            let b = barrier.clone();
            let r = results.clone();
            spawn(async move {
                let should_cancel = (seed + i) % 3 == 0;
                if should_cancel {
                    cx.cancel_after(Duration::from_micros(seed * 10));
                }
                match b.wait(&cx).await {
                    Ok(result) => r.lock().push((i, "proceeded", result.is_leader)),
                    Err(_) => r.lock().push((i, "cancelled", false)),
                }
            });
        }

        // Verify invariants
        let r = results.lock();
        let proceeded = r.iter().filter(|x| x.1 == "proceeded").count();
        let cancelled = r.iter().filter(|x| x.1 == "cancelled").count();
        assert!(proceeded == 10 || proceeded == 0, "Partial barrier trip");
        if proceeded > 0 {
            assert_eq!(r.iter().filter(|x| x.2).count(), 1, "Exactly one leader");
        }
    }
}
```

